\begin_layout Standard
A 50Ω/45W thick-film resistor dissipates the input RF power 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{in}$
\end_inset

.
 This resistor is housed in a surface-mount package with heatsink pad in
 contact with the top and bottom ground pours on the circuit board.
 The board itself serves as the heatsink and its heat capacity limits the
 maximum time the load is able to withstand input power without damaging
 the resistive element.
 See the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "subsec:Thermal-Considerations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 Section for details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Manufacturing variation of the load resistance introduces error in the power
 reading.
 The nominal load resistance is 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{load}=50\Omega$
\end_inset

 with a tolerance of 
\begin_inset Formula $t=1\%$
\end_inset

 and temperature coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=100$
\end_inset

ppm/℃.
 Over the industrial temperature range, the maximum error in the load resistance
 is then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta R_{load}=(t/100)R_{load}+(\alpha/10^{6})R_{load}\times65$
\end_inset

℃, which comes out to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta R_{load}=0.825\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 The maximum error in the power reading is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta P_{err}\approx P_{in}\frac{\Delta R_{load}}{R_{load}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
