\begin_layout Subsection*
Peak Detector
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Peak-Detector"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The unit employs a BAT46 Schottky diode and two parallel-connected 5.6nF
 capacitors to detect the envelope of the RF input voltage.
 Positive half-cycles of the input forward bias the diode and charge the
 capacitors to the peak input voltage 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{pk}$
\end_inset

; in negative half-cycles, the diode is reverse biased with a maximum reverse
 voltage of 
\begin_inset Formula $\max(V_{R})=2V_{pk}$
\end_inset

.
 Reverse breakdown occurs at 100V for BAT46, limiting the peak input voltage
 to 50V and the input power to 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{pk}^{2}/2R_{load}=50^{2}/100=25$
\end_inset

W.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The voltage divider loads the peak detector, somewhat reducing its accuracy.
 The total resistance of the divider is 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{div}=110k\Omega$
\end_inset

, drawing a current of approximately 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{div}=V_{pk}/R_{div}$
\end_inset

 or about 450μA at 50V envelope voltage.
 The diode must conduct this current in positive half-cycles to charge the
 capacitors, resulting in a forward voltage drop 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{F}$
\end_inset

 across the diode near 0.3V.
 The error in the power reading due to to an error in the measured peak
 voltage of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V_{err}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta P_{err}\approx\Delta V_{err}\cdot\sqrt{\frac{2P_{in}}{R_{load}}}\label{eq:p_error}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{in}$
\end_inset

 is the input power and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{load}=50\Omega$
\end_inset

 is the load resistance.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V_{err}=V_{F}$
\end_inset

, the error due to the diode drop is about 0.06W for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{in}=1.0$
\end_inset

W; for 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{in}=20$
\end_inset

W, it is about 0.27W.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The μDummy load measures the voltage across a dc-biased BAT46 diode to partially
 compensate the drop in the peak detector.
 A diode from the same production lot as the detector diode is forward biased
 by the envelope voltage and a 100kΩ resistor.
 The PIC18 samples the forward voltage across this compensation diode 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{F(comp)}$
\end_inset

 and, from this measurement, computes the forward voltage drop across the
 detector diode 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{F}$
\end_inset

 as follows.
 When forward voltage exceeds several tens of millivolts, the detector and
 compensation diode currents are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
I & \approx I_{s}e^{V/\eta V_{T}}\\
I_{comp} & \approx I_{s}e^{V_{F(comp)}/\eta V_{T}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{s}$
\end_inset

 is a diode parameter called the saturation current, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{T}$
\end_inset

 is the thermal voltage equal to 0.0259V at room temperature, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is the diode ideality factor near 1.0 for Schottky diodes.
 Dividing the first equation by the second and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{F}$
\end_inset

 results in the formula
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{F}=V_{F(comp)}+V_{T}\ln\left(\frac{I}{I_{comp}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The saturation current 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{s}$
\end_inset

 cancels out since the diodes are matched.
 This equation can be further reduced by noting the compensation diode current
 is 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{comp}\approx V_{pk}/R_{comp}$
\end_inset

,where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{comp}=100$
\end_inset

kΩ is the biasing resistance and the average detector diode current is 
\begin_inset Formula $I\approx V_{pk}/(R_{div}||R_{comp})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{div}=110$
\end_inset

kΩ is the voltage divider resistance:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V_{F}=V_{F(comp)}+V_{T}\ln\left(1+\frac{R_{comp}}{R_{div}}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
At room temperature, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{F}=V_{F(comp)}+0.017$
\end_inset

V; the detector diode voltage equals the compensator diode voltage plus
 about 17mV.
 The change in the 17mV offset is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm4.0$
\end_inset

mV over the -40℃ to +85℃ industrial temperature range and is neglected in
 this application due to lack of a calibrated temperature sensor.
 The PIC18 contains an internal temperature sensor that could be manually
 calibrated for this application, though this will do little to improve
 the overall compensation accuracy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This method of compensation still results in error due to diode mismatch
 and differences in the conduction methods.
 The compensation diode is dc-biased, while the current through the detector
 diode flows in pulses, remaining near zero except at peaks of the RF input,
 during which the instantaneous detector current 
\begin_inset Formula $i(t)$
\end_inset

 will exceed the averaged current 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 used in the above equations.
 This causes the detector diode's forward voltage drop to exceed the figures
 predicted by the foregoing equations.
 Suppose the error in 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{F}$
\end_inset

 is limited to about 0.1V maximum.
 The resulting error in the power reading is then 0.09W when the input power
 is 20W and 0.02W when the input power is 1W.
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Increasing the voltage divider resistance will reduce the diode drop.
 Doing so, however, will require insertion of a buffer amplifier at the
 output of the voltage divider to lower the A/D input impedance below 10kΩ.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{os}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{os}$
\end_inset

 are the input voltage and current offsets of an op amp connected in a unity
 buffer configuration with feedback resistor equal to the parallel combination
 of the voltage divider resistors 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{||}=R_{top}R_{bottom}/(R_{top}+R_{bottom})$
\end_inset

, the error in the envelope voltage is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Delta V_{err}=V_{F}'+(V_{os}+I_{os}R_{||})A_{div}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{F}'$
\end_inset

 is the forward diode drop under the reduced loading and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{div}$
\end_inset

 is the division factor of the voltage divider.
 The error in the power reading is then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P_{err}\approx\Delta V_{err}\cdot\sqrt{2P_{in}/R_{load}}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{top}=10$
\end_inset

MΩ, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{bottom}=1.0$
\end_inset

MΩ, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{os}=1$
\end_inset

mV, 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{os}=2$
\end_inset

pA, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{F}'=0.17$
\end_inset

V, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta V_{err}\approx0.2$
\end_inset

V.
 At 1W input power, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P_{err}\approx0.04$
\end_inset

W; at 20W input power 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta P_{err}\approx0.18$
\end_inset

W.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Microcontroller and Display
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A surface-mount package houses the PIC18 to reduce board area and routing
 complexity.
 This PIC18 is powered from a 5V linear regulator and is clocked by an internal
 1MHz oscillator (HFINTOSC).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Power readings are output to a three-digit transflective LCD where the digits
 are 7-segmented.
 To 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

activate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a segment of a particular digit, the PIC18 alternates the voltage applied
 to that segment between +5V and -5V at a rate of 30Hz; to disable a segment,
 the PIC18 drives the segment voltage to zero.
 One side of the LCD segments contact a common line labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

COM
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and separate lines expose the other sides of the segments.
 There are a total of 24 lines on the display (COM line, 21 segment lines,
 and 2 decimal point lines), but the PIC18 has enough outputs to drive only
 two complete digits.
 The meter need only read up to 20.0W, and thus the first digit is wired
 to display the numbers 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

2
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 only, reducing the pin count.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When driving the LCD and performing periodic A/D conversions, the PIC18
 draws about 800μA from the linear regulator.
 The external voltage reference draws an additional 600μA from the regulator,
 and the quiescent current of the linear regulator is about 600μA.
 The combined power draw of the PIC18 and voltage reference from the RF
 input is then 
\begin_inset Formula $(800+600+600)\mu A\cdot V_{pk}$
\end_inset

.
 Add to this the power dissipated by the envelope voltage divider and compensati
on diode 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{pk}^{2}/(R_{div}||R_{comp})$
\end_inset

 and the total parasitic power draw is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{parasitic}=(2.0+V_{pk}/52.4)mA\cdot V_{pk}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
With 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{pk}=45V$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{in}\approx20.0$
\end_inset

W), 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{parasitic}=0.148$
\end_inset

W; with 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{pk}=10V$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $P_{in}\approx1.0W$
\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{parasitic}=0.022$
\end_inset

W.
 This parasitic power draw constitutes error in the power reading.
\end_layout

