\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Thermal Diagram
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Thermal-Diagram"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the model, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{e}$
\end_inset

 is the temperature of the resistive element, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{b}$
\end_inset

 is the temperature of the board (assumed isothermal for simplicity), and
 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{a}$
\end_inset

 is the temperature of the surroundings.
 The thermal resistance 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{eb}$
\end_inset

 is a measure of the opposition that the resistor's casing presents to heat
 flow from the internal resistive element to the heatsink pad—i.e from the
 element (e) and the board (b).
 For the Ohmite part used in this application, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{eb}=3$
\end_inset

℃/W.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{ba}$
\end_inset

 is the heat resistance between the board and the surroundings.
 Its value depends on the size of the board, air flow rate, and other factors.
 Last, 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{b}$
\end_inset

 is the heat capacity of the board and may be approximated as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{b}\approx m_{Cu}c_{Cu}+m_{FR4}c_{FR4}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
where 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{Cu}$
\end_inset

 is the total mass of copper on the board, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{Cu}$
\end_inset

 is the specific heat capacity of copper, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{FR4}$
\end_inset

 is the mass of FR-4 dielectric in the board's interior, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{FR4}$
\end_inset

 is the specific heat capacity of FR-4.
 Substituting the appropriate values, we find 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{b}\approx4.3$
\end_inset

J/℃ for the μDummy load board.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{ba}>>r_{eb}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{ba}$
\end_inset

 may be neglected, the initial temperature of the board is equal to the
 ambient 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{b}(0)=T_{a}$
\end_inset

, and that constant RF power 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{in}$
\end_inset

 is applied starting at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, the solution for 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{e}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{e}(t)\approx\frac{P_{in}}{C_{b}}t+P_{in}r_{eb}+T_{a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The temperature of the resistive element increases linearly with time, eventuall
y growing large enough to damage the resistor if the input RF power is not
 removed.
 According to the power derating curve in the resistor's data-sheet, to
 safely dissipate the full rated power of 20W, the element must be held
 below about 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{e(max)}=110$
\end_inset

℃.
 The time at which 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{e}$
\end_inset

 reaches 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{e(max)}$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t_{max}=C_{b}\left(\frac{T_{e(max)}-T_{a}}{P_{in}}-r_{eb}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
A plot of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{max}$
\end_inset

 versus the input power appears in the 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand nameref
reference "sec:Overview"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 Section at several ambient temperature values.
 The safe operating time predicted by this formula is somewhat pessimistic
 since we neglect heat lost to convection and radation from the board to
 the ambient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After we remove the input power, the temperature of the board decays exponential
ly to ambient with the termal time constant
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tau=r_{ba}C_{b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
which is the time required for the board temperature to decay to 37% of
 its initial value above ambient.
 Based on empirical observation, the board-to-ambient thermal resistance
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{ba}$
\end_inset

 is approximately 30℃/W (indoors with minimal air flow).
 The time constant is then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=(30)(4.3)=129$
\end_inset

 sec.
 The 80% cool-down time (the time required for the board to reach 20% of
 its initial value above ambient) is 
\begin_inset Formula $1.6\tau=206$
\end_inset

 sec, or about 3.5 minutes.
\end_layout

